<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="0.5" to="2" step="0.5"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="m" from="2" to="4" step="1" exclude="$k"/>
  
  <function name="r1x"> $m*x </function>
  <function name="r2x"> $k*x^2 </function>
  <function name="r1y" variable="y"> sqrt(y/$k) </function>
  <function name="r2y" variable="y"> y/$m </function>
  
  <function name="gx"> pi*(($r1x)^2 - ($r2x)^2)</function>
  <function name="Gx"> pi*($m^2/3*x^3 - $k^2/5*x^5)</function>

  <function name="gy" variable="y"> pi*(($r1y)^2 - ($r2y)^2)</function>
  <function name="Gy" variable="y"> pi*(1/(2*$k)*y^2 - 1/(3*$m^2)*y^3)</function>

  <math name="a">0</math>
  <math name="b">$m/$k</math>

  <math name="c">0</math>
  <math name="d">$m^2/$k</math>
  
  <math name="intValueX" simplify>$$Gx($b)-$$Gx($a)</math>
  <math name="intValueY" simplify>$$Gy($d)-$$Gy($c)</math>

  <mathList name="intPoints">(0,0) ($m/$k, $m^2/$k)</mathList>

</setup>  

  <p>
    Consider the finite region, <m>\mathcal{R}</m>, that is bounded by the curves 
    <me>y = $m x, \ y = $k x^2</me>    
  </p>

  <p> 
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Sketch a graph of the region, <m>\mathcal{R}</m>, and find the exact locations of the intersection points of the two curves.  Enter the intersection points as ordered pairs; separate multiple points with commas.
        </p>
        <p>
          The curves intersect at the points: <answer unorderedCompare simplifyOnCompare>$intPoints</answer>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Find an integral expression that represents the volume of the resulting solid of revolution when <m>\mathcal{R}</m> is revolved about the <m>x</m>-axis.  Do so by filling in the blanks below; once you identify the lower and upper limits of integration, those numbers will appear in the integral expression below.
        </p>

        <p>
          lower limit of integration: <m>a = </m> <answer name="lower">$a</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          upper limit of integration: <m>b = </m> <answer name="upper">$b</answer>
        </p>

        <p>
          Integral expression for the volume, <m>V</m>, of the solid of revolution when revolved about the <m>x</m>-axis: 
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>V = \displaystyle\int_{$lower}^{$upper}</m><mathInput name="int1" minWidth="100" /><m>d</m><mathInput name="dWhat" minWidth="15"/><answer simplifyOnCompare><award><when>$int1 = $gx and $dWhat = x</when></award></answer> <!--, <m>$$f($h), $$g($h), $f - $g</m> -->
        </p> 
        <p>
          Evaluate the integral to find the numerical value of the volume, <m>V</m>, and report the value below.  Report your result to an accuracy within <m>0.0001</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>V = </m><mathInput name="intValx" minWidth="40" /> <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.0001" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award><when>$intValueX=$intValx </when></award></answer>
        </p>  
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Find an integral expression that represents the volume of the resulting solid of revolution when <m>\mathcal{R}</m> is revolved about the <m>y</m>-axis.  Do so by filling in the blanks below; once you identify the lower and upper limits of integration, those numbers will appear in the integral expression below.
        </p>

        <p>
          lower limit of integration: <m>c = </m> <answer name="lower">$c</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          upper limit of integration: <m>d = </m> <answer name="upper">$d</answer>
        </p>

        <p>
          Integral expression for the volume, <m>W</m>, of the solid of revolution when revolved about the <m>y</m>-axis: 
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>W = \displaystyle\int_{$lower}^{$upper}</m><mathInput name="int2" minWidth="100" /><m>d</m><mathInput name="dWhat2" minWidth="15"/><answer simplifyOnCompare><award><when>$int2 = $gy and $dWhat2 = y</when></award></answer> <!--, <m>$$f($h), $$g($h), $f - $g</m> -->
        </p> 
        <p>
          Evaluate the integral to find the numerical value of the volume, <m>W</m>, and report the value below.  Report your result to an accuracy within <m>0.0001</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>W = </m><mathInput name="intValy" minWidth="40" /> <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.0001" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award><when>$intValueY=$intValy </when></award></answer>
        </p>  
      </li>      
    </ol>
  </p>